      <hedline>
        <hl1>Frustrated Customers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lee Goeller letter on July 20 article on the poor quality of customer service in high-tech retailing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>So the American Customer Satisfaction Index has dropped since 1994, the year the Bell System breakup was completed. What did we expect when the concept of service was destroyed to force increased sale of product?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>So the American Customer Satisfaction Index has dropped since 1994, the year the Bell System breakup was completed. What did we expect when the concept of service was destroyed to force increased sale of product?</p>
        <p>When you buy a service, you don't pay if the service is not rendered. This gives the service company every incentive to provide customer support. Contrast this with selling a product. The vendor has all the profit before the customer gets any service, and manufacturers invent an infinite number of ways to force customers to keep buying the same product over and over, not to get new and wonderful functions, but simply in the hope that previous mistakes will have been corrected.</p>
        <p>LEE GOELLER  Haddonfield, N.J.</p>
      </block>
